<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="30.[189,343,574,605]" box="[189,343,574,605]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,343,574,605]" fontSize="13" level="1" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" reason="0">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,343,574,605]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Discussion</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[189,1399,628,936]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
Among the nine species of the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[626,797,628,654]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Trichomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[626,797,628,654]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Trichomyrmex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
reported from the Arabian Peninsula, 
<taxonomicName box="[1251,1346,629,654]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Trichomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mayri">
<emphasis box="[1251,1346,629,654]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">T. mayri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[189,339,663,689]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Trichomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="destructor">
<emphasis box="[189,339,663,689]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">T. destructor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the most abundant ones. However, 
<taxonomicName box="[790,884,664,689]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Trichomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mayri">
<emphasis box="[790,884,664,689]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">T. mayri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the most successfully distributed species, since it has the ability to establish itself in a broad range of habitats, including desert and agricultural, wild and urban, pristine and disturbed sites (
<bibRefCitation author="Collingwood C. A." box="[779,1009,733,760]" journalOrPublisher="Formicidae of Saudi Arabia. Fauna of Saudi Arabia" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="230 - 302" part="7" refString="Collingwood C. A. 1985. Hymenoptera: Fam. Formicidae of Saudi Arabia. Fauna of Saudi Arabia 7: 230 - 302." title="Hymenoptera: Fam" type="journal article" year="1985">Collingwood 1985</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Collingwood C. A. &amp; Agosti D." box="[1029,1393,734,760]" journalOrPublisher="Fauna of Saudi Arabia" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="300 - 385" part="15" refString="Collingwood C. A. &amp; Agosti D. 1996. Formicidae (Insecta: Hymenoptera) of Saudi Arabia (Part 2). Fauna of Saudi Arabia 15: 300 - 385." title="Formicidae (Insecta: Hymenoptera) of Saudi Arabia (Part 2)" type="journal article" year="1996">Collingwood &amp; Agosti 1996</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Collingwood C. A. &amp; Tigar B. J. &amp; Agosti D." box="[189,482,769,795]" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Arid Environments" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="505 - 512" part="37" publicationUrl="http://dx.doi.org/10.1006/jare.1997.0309" refString="Collingwood C. A., Tigar B. J. &amp; Agosti D. 1997. Introduced ants in the United Arab Emirates. Journal of Arid Environments 37: 505 - 512. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1006 / jare. 1997.0309" title="Introduced ants in the United Arab Emirates" type="journal article" year="1997">
Collingwood 
<emphasis box="[353,415,769,795]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">et al.</emphasis>
1997
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Collingwood C. A. &amp; Agosti D. &amp; Sharaf M. R. &amp; Harten A." box="[495,553,769,795]" journalOrPublisher="Arthropod Fauna of the United Arab Emirates" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="405 - 474" part="4" refString="Collingwood C. A., Agosti D., Sharaf M. R. &amp; Harten A. 2011. Order Hymenoptera, Family Formicidae. Arthropod Fauna of the United Arab Emirates 4: 405 - 474." title="Order Hymenoptera, Family Formicidae" type="journal article" year="2011">2011</bibRefCitation>
). These observations agree with 
<bibRefCitation author="Collingwood C. A. &amp; Pohl H. &amp; Gusten R. &amp; Wranik W. &amp; Harten A." box="[950,1261,769,795]" journalOrPublisher="Fauna of Arabia" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="473 - 495" part="20" refString="Collingwood C. A., Pohl H., Gusten R., Wranik W. &amp; Harten A. 2004. The ants (Insecta: Hymenoptera: Formicidae) of the Socotra Archipelago. Fauna of Arabia 20: 473 - 495." title="The ants (Insecta: Hymenoptera: Formicidae) of the Socotra Archipelago" type="journal article" year="2004">
Collingwood 
<emphasis box="[1115,1176,769,795]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">et al.</emphasis>
(2004)
</bibRefCitation>
and Sharaf 
<emphasis box="[189,246,804,830]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">et al.</emphasis>
(in press) on Socotra, where 
<taxonomicName box="[578,672,805,830]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Trichomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mayri">
<emphasis box="[578,672,805,830]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">T. mayri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a broad distributional range on the Archipelago, occurring in different habitats. The species is also recorded from different localities in Egypt, including the Sinai and Nile Delta (
<bibRefCitation author="Sharaf M. R." box="[375,525,874,901]" journalOrPublisher="Ain Shams University, Faculty of Science, Entomology Department, Cairo [unpublished thesis]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" refString="Sharaf M. R. 2006. Taxonomic and Ecological Studies on Family Formicidae (Order: Hymenoptera) in Egypt including some Protectorates with a Study of some Insect Fauna associated with Ant Species. Ain Shams University, Faculty of Science, Entomology Department, Cairo [unpublished thesis]." title="Taxonomic and Ecological Studies on Family Formicidae (Order: Hymenoptera) in Egypt including some Protectorates with a Study of some Insect Fauna associated with Ant Species" type="book" year="2006">Sharaf 2006</bibRefCitation>
). The two species are recorded here for the first time from Qatar, which is not surprising, especially under the intensive urbanization that has occurred recently (UNCSD 2004).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[189,1399,975,1354]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<taxonomicName box="[189,436,975,1001]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Trichomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mayri">
<emphasis box="[189,436,975,1001]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Trichomyrmex mayri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[657,809,975,1001]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Trichomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="destructor">
<emphasis box="[657,809,975,1001]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">T. destructor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in all morphological characters except the colour, which is uniform dark brown in the former and yellow to brown yellow with a dark brown gaster in the latter. Although the separation of species based on colour is a feeble character, especially for genera that having distinct colour variation, like 
<taxonomicName box="[628,799,1081,1107]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Trichomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[628,799,1081,1107]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Trichomyrmex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[858,1019,1082,1107]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Monomorium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[858,1019,1082,1107]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Monomorium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it is observed that the colour is consistent for the studied material of both species in the Arabian Peninsula; therefore, we treat both as valid species. However, it is likely that a future probability for synonymizing 
<taxonomicName box="[1142,1212,1152,1177]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Trichomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mayri">
<emphasis box="[1142,1212,1152,1177]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">mayri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1276,1399,1151,1177]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Trichomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="destructor">
<emphasis box="[1276,1399,1151,1177]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">destructor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
exists especially when using molecular techniques. 
<taxonomicName box="[802,1117,1186,1212]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Trichomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="abyssinicus">
<emphasis box="[802,1117,1186,1212]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Trichomyrmex abyssinicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is reported here for the first time from Saudi Arabia. The newly described species 
<taxonomicName box="[877,1038,1222,1248]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Trichomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="almosayari" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[877,1038,1222,1248]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">T. almosayari</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1044,1133,1222,1248]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1188,1304,1222,1248]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Trichomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shakeri" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1188,1304,1222,1248]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">T. shakeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1311,1399,1222,1248]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
appear to be restricted to Riyadh Province (Central region). Relatively few specimens of the three species have been collected despite intensive efforts using a variety of sampling methods. All specimens were collected using pitfall traps.
</paragraph>
